AGI - The situation in Ukraine continues to evolve rapidly, with important developments on the military and diplomatic front. The commander of the Ukrainian army, Oleksandr Syrsky, > meant a possible reposition of troops in the Russian region of Kursk>, an area where Moscow recently claimed significant territorial advances. "My priority remains to save the lives of Ukrainian soldiers, and for this reason the units of defense forces, if necessary, manoeuvre towards more favorable positions," he wrote on Facebook, using a language that often implies a strategic retreat.
At the same time, the Russian chief of state, Valery Gerasimov, > informed President Vladimir Putin > of the capture of 430 Ukrainian soldiers in the Kursk region. Putin stated that prisoners will be treated as terrorists according to the laws of the Russian Federation, meaning they could face long trials and severe penalties. The Russian strategy seems to be oriented towards the creation of a "security zone" along the state border in the Kursk region. During a visit to the place of command of the Kursk force group, Putin reiterated the need to completely free the territory from every Ukrainian presence, underlining that military operations will continue until this goal is reached.
<div </div
On the diplomatic front, the President of the United States, Donald Trump, expressed the hope that Vladimir Putin accepts the proposal of a 30-day ceasefire agreed during the Gedda negotiations. "We hope that we can get a ceasefire from Russia," Trump said, adding that the United States has financial pressure tools that could have a devastating impact on Moscow, but that at the moment does not intend to use to promote peace.
Trump defined the understanding of Gedda "a great success", stating that the responsibility for the implementation of the ceasefire now falls on Russia. "If we could, we would have done 80% of the route to end this bloodbath," he said. The American Special Envoy, Steve Witkoff, <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-03-12/ucraina-house-white-inviato-a-mosca-in-settimana-30409028/"> is leaving for Moscow</a> to discuss the agreement, while the American President has avoided meeting. Despite the difficulties in the negotiations, Trump said that Kiev is now more likely to reach a peace agreement, recalling past tensions with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky.> The future of the crisis remains uncertain, with ongoing military operations and diplomacy seeking a sustainable solution to the conflict.
