AGI - When they saw him approaching, Israeli soldiers did not believe in their eyes. Get used to seeing Palestinian children grow up too quickly they didn't trust the little one who headed safely to their post. But they kept calm and when he was close enough to talk to him they asked him what he wanted. The child, just 4 years old, had no hesitation: "Hamas sends me" he said.
&nbsp;
The episode, which with the climate of tension in the Gaza Strip could have had a dramatic outcome, ended with the soldiers who accompanied the child to Gaza, but it was an opportunity, for the Israeli army, to remember how the Palestinian militiamen do not hesitate "to use any means and cynically exploit civilians and children to get their terrorist goals".
&nbsp;
While not specifying it, the reference of the Israeli army is to the use of kamikaze children, atrocious war crimes very frequent in the world, especially in Africa and the Middle East. From Boko Haram to Isis, to Islamist groups in Pakistan, Somalia and Yemen, there are several terrorist organizations recruiting, indoctrinating and forcing children to commit atrocities.
&nbsp;
As Human Rights Watch has repeatedly denounced, kamikaze children were used during the civil war in Syria by different groups of armed opposition, such as the Free Syrian Army, the Islamic Front, the Nusra Front and the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant. You can't forget the footage made a couple of years ago in the Isis training camps that portrayed child soldiers, children boia in mass executions filmed and children kamikaze.
&nbsp;
The Caliphate of the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria over the years has used Yazidi kidnapped kids and brainwashed as suicide bombers against Iraqi loyalist troops. But they are not only jihadist groups to use children and adolescents to carry out actions of terrorism and war. Minors have fought and are still fighting in Burma, Sudan, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Yemen.
&nbsp;
It is difficult to estimate today how many children are currently employed as soldiers, but according to UNICEF only in South Sudan thousands are used by groups and armed forces. The Statute of the International Criminal Court, approved in 1998 puts as a crime of war the recruitment of children under 15 years of age in national armed forces and their use in active participation in hostilities in both international and internal conflicts, while the Oil Convention No. 182 - International Labour Organization, approved in 1999, defines the forced and compulsory recruitment of children one of the "serious forms of child labour" and prohibits it.
&nbsp;
According to the latest Unicef data, over the last twenty years there have been more than 315.000 serious violations on children and children, committed by the belligerents in more than 30 situations of conflict in Africa, Asia, Medioriente and Latin America: at least 120,000 children killed or mutilated, 105.000 recruited or used in conflicts, 32,500 those kidnapped, 16,000 victims of sexual violence. &nbsp;
